Comparisons of rainfall regime among vegetation types and Biomes

Marcio

7/15/2023

Here, we investigate differences in mean annual precipitation (MAP), Markham seasonality index (MSI) (Markham, 1970) and interannual variability (CV) between the Amazon biome, the Cerrado biome, and three vegetation types within the Cerrado (i.e. Savanna, Gallery Forest, and Dry Forest).

Methods and Results

The visual inspection of the residuals distribution show that it is normaly distributed, with the mean near zero (Figure 1).

lm(Rainfall ~ as.factor(Biome),
   data = data)$resid %>% hist

Figure 1: Residuals inspection.

Firstly, we used the gls function from the R package nlme (Pinheiro et al., 2019) to fit a linear mixed-effects model. This model considered rainfall as the response variable, with the factors of interest being Biome (with two categories: Amazon and Cerrado) and Vegetation Type (with three categories: Savanna, Gallery Forest, and Dry Forest) (Table 1).

m1 <- nlme::gls(Rainfall ~ as.factor(Biome),
    data = data,
    weights = nlme::varIdent(form = ~ 1 | as.factor(Biome)),
    method = "ML", na.action = na.omit) 

summary(m1)$tTable
##                                    Value Std.Error   t-value p-value
## (Intercept)                    2154.8444  1.113976 1934.3723       0
## as.factor(Biome)Cerrado        -718.4042  1.559074 -460.7891       0
## as.factor(Biome)Dry Forest     -859.0067 19.926527  -43.1087       0
## as.factor(Biome)Gallery Forest -753.3591  2.908315 -259.0363       0
## as.factor(Biome)Savanna        -745.8401  2.143943 -347.8824       0

Next, we performed an analysis of variance (ANOVA) using the anova function in R to assess the statistical significance of the main effects and the interaction between the factors.

an_m <- anova(m1)
an_m %>% data.frame
##                  numDF    F.value p.value
## (Intercept)          1 6081108.92       0
## as.factor(Biome)     4   65743.13       0

ANOVA revealed statistically significant results (Table 2) and we proceeded with post hoc tests to conduct multiple comparisons between groups. For this purpose, we utilized the emmeans function from the package emmeans (Lenth, 2022) to compute adjusted means and confidence intervals for each combination of factors (Table 3).

means <- emmeans::emmeans(m1, specs = list("Biome"))
means %>% data.frame
##            Biome   emmean        SE           df lower.CL upper.CL
## 1         Amazon 2154.844  1.113976 1.643082e+05 2151.975 2157.714
## 2        Cerrado 1436.440  1.090765 5.897248e+04 1433.630 1439.250
## 3     Dry Forest 1295.838 19.895365 6.894118e+00 1225.848 1365.827
## 4 Gallery Forest 1401.485  2.686513 7.553076e+00 1392.314 1410.657
## 5        Savanna 1409.004  1.831816 7.224685e+00 1402.661 1415.347

Subsequently, we conducted multiple comparison tests using the contrast function, also from emmeans package, with the argument method = “pairwise”. This test allowed us to identify significant differences between groups (or not) by comparing all factor levels, such as biomes and vegetation types. Adjusted p-values were considered to control the family-wise error rate.

contrasts <- emmeans::contrast(means, method = "pairwise")

contrasts %>%
  data.frame %>%
  rename(Pair = "emmeans.of.Biome.contrast") %>% 
  rename(estimate = "emmeans.of.Biome.estimate") %>% 
  rename(se = "emmeans.of.Biome.SE") %>% 
  rename(df = "emmeans.of.Biome.df") %>% 
  rename(`t ratio` = "emmeans.of.Biome.t.ratio") %>% 
  rename(`p-value` = "emmeans.of.Biome.p.value")

We found differences in MAP between dry forests and both gallery forests and savannas (Table 4). Unexpectedly, the MAP of our samples are distinct from the MAP of both Biomes, including the Cerrado where they are located (Table 4).

Furthermore, we found that the MAP for more than half of all dry forests samples are outside the bistability zone (1300-2100 mm), i.e. the range of MAP in which forests and savannas may occur, defined by Ciemer et al. (2019) for the neotropics (Figure 2). However they are near the lower limit. Despite the unexpected differences in dry forests MAP, most of our samples are inside the bistability zone for the neotropics (1300-2100mm; Ciemer et al., 2019) (Figure 2). Staver et al. (2011) defined a more wide range (1000-2500 mm), but using a global model. However, the Staver et al. (2011) model correctly includes dry forests in the bistability zone.

Markham Seasonality Index (MSI)

To compare between vegetation types and Biomes regardind MSI (i.e. seasonality lenght) (Markham, 1970), we performed the same method used to test for differences in MAP (Tables 5-8).

m2 <- nlme::gls(Rainfall ~ as.factor(Biome),
    data = data1,
    weights = nlme::varIdent(form = ~ 1 | as.factor(Biome)),
    method = "ML", na.action = na.omit) 

summary(m2)$tTable

Interannual variability

We calculated the interannual variability using the coefficient of variation of annual precipitation (CV).

The differences between biomes and among vegetation types were tested with the method used for MAP and MSI.

m3 <- nlme::gls(Rainfall ~ as.factor(Biome),
    data = data2,
    weights = nlme::varIdent(form = ~ 1 | as.factor(Biome)),
    method = "ML", na.action = na.omit) 

summary(m3)$tTable
##                                     Value    Std.Error   t-value p-value

## as.factor(Biome)Cerrado        0.02282310 5.510988e-05  414.1381       0
## as.factor(Biome)Dry Forest     0.02664567 2.262253e-04  117.7838       0
## as.factor(Biome)Gallery Forest 0.02407571 8.696727e-05  276.8365       0
## as.factor(Biome)Savanna        0.02430212 7.273871e-05  334.1016       0

The ANOVA revealed significative differences among groups (Table 10).

an_m <- anova(m3)
an_m %>% data.frame
##                  numDF    F.value p.value
## (Intercept)          1 8919854.23       0

The range of values of CV is very similar among the sampled vegetation types, with the exception of dry forests. We also found differences among vegetation types and Cerrado biome, with our samples being outside the upper limit of Cerrado (Table 11). The range of CV values for the Amazon biome also differs from the other groups in relation to CV and do not overlap with Cerrado nor with our samples (Table 11; Figure 4).

Conclusion

Despite differences showed in the analysis of MAP, MSI and CV for our sampled vegetation types, the values are very close and vegetation types are inside the bistability zone for MAP defined by Staver et al. (2011).
